## Context

All sliding-window null models (S1–S4, L1–L2, C2ST, G1–G9) use Monte
Carlo permutation (n_perm=500 full Fisher-Yates shuffles of the
before+after pool).  Monte Carlo remains the production path for all
methods.

The analytical null is implemented as a **validation control**: for
methods where E[T | H₀] and Var[T | H₀] have closed-form expressions
(S1, S2, L1, C2ST), the analytical values provide a ground truth to check
that the Monte Carlo estimates are unbiased and well-converged.

Use cases:
- Catch bugs in permutation drivers (a driver that returns wrong null_mean
  will diverge from the analytical value).
- Quantify the Monte Carlo error (|analytical − MC| / SE) as a diagnostic.
- Optionally run in CI as a regression test: if MC drifts >2 SE from
  analytical, the test fails.

G methods (G1, G5, G6, G8) lack simple closed forms; they remain
Monte Carlo only.  The analytical control is not applicable to them.

## Permutation structure

Each (year, window) test pools n_before + n_after documents and shuffles
ALL of them (full Fisher-Yates permutation), reassigning the first n_before
to "before" and the rest to "after".  Only documents within the window
participate — the full corpus is never touched outside the window.

## Analytical nulls by method

### S2 — energy distance
E(D_energy | H₀) = 2 * E[||X−Y||] − E[||X−X'||] − E[||Y−Y'||]
where X, Y drawn iid from the pooled empirical distribution.
These expectations are means of entries in the pairwise distance matrix,
computable in O(N²) from the pooled embeddings.
Var can be derived from 4th-moment U-statistics (see Székely & Rizzo 2013).

### S1 — MMD²
E(MMD² | H₀) = 0 (biased estimator) or
E(MMD²_unbiased | H₀) = 0 by construction.
Var(MMD²_unbiased | H₀) from Gretton et al. (2012) Lemma 6:
  Var ≈ (4/n²) × (Var of h(X,X') under H₀)
where h is the kernel function.  Exact in O(N²).

### L1 — JS divergence
Under H₀ (shared vocabulary distribution), JS divergence between two
multinomial samples of sizes n_before, n_after from shared distribution p
satisfies:
  E[JS] ≈ (V−1)/(4) × (1/n_before + 1/n_after)   (leading term)
  Var[JS] = O(1/n²)
where V = vocabulary size.  This is the first-order analytic correction
(Archer et al. 2014).  Requires only the pooled TF-IDF mean and vocabulary
size — O(V) to compute.

### G methods (G1, G5, G6, G8) — citation scalar metrics
These compute |Δ metric(before) − Δ metric(after)| where the metric is
a summary of a citation graph.  Under node-label permutation, the analytic
null requires the variance of the metric under uniform random node splits.
This is harder; leave for a follow-up unless easy closed forms exist.

### C2ST — AUC
Under H₀ (no separability), AUC → 0.5 with variance O(1/(n_before*n_after))
from the Mann-Whitney U-statistic identity.  Exact analytic null available
via Hanley & McNeil (1982).

## Relevant files

- `scripts/compute_null_model.py` — dispatcher; add `--analytical` flag
- `scripts/_permutation_accel.py` — GPU/CPU permutation backends; add
  analytical implementations alongside Monte Carlo
- `scripts/_permutation_lexical.py` — L1/L2 backends
- `scripts/_permutation_citation.py` — G method backends
- `config/analysis.yaml` — add `analytical: true` toggle per method

## Actions

1. Add `analytical_null(method, X_before, X_after) → (null_mean, null_std)`
   in `_permutation_accel.py` for S1 and S2.  Does NOT replace the MC
   path; called separately.

2. Add analytical null for L1 (JS divergence) in `_permutation_lexical.py`.

3. Add analytical null for C2ST (AUC / Mann-Whitney) in
   `_divergence_c2st.py` or a helper.

4. Add `scripts/validate_null_model.py` — for each (year, window) pair
   in a method's null CSV, compute the analytical null_mean and null_std
   and report |MC − analytical| / SE(MC).  Output a summary table and
   WARN if any row exceeds 3 SE.

5. Add a `make validate-null` target in `divergence.mk` that runs the
   validator for S1, S2, L1, C2ST.

6. Optionally wire `validate-null` into `make check` as a soft check
   (non-blocking; only warns).

## Test

Red: in `tests/test_analytical_null.py`, assert that for a synthetic
fixture (n_before=n_after=200, Gaussian embeddings), the analytical
null_mean and null_std for S2 agree with Monte Carlo (n_perm=5000)
within 2 SE.  Same for L1 (multinomial fixture) and C2ST (iid labels).

## Verification

- [ ] Analytical values agree with MC (n_perm=5000) within 2 SE on fixture
- [ ] `make validate-null` runs and produces a summary with no >3 SE rows
  on the real corpus null CSVs
- [ ] Monte Carlo null CSVs are unchanged
- [ ] `make check-fast` passes

## Invariants

- Production null CSVs (tab_null_*.csv) are generated by Monte Carlo
  only; analytical values are never written to those files.
- Output CSV schema unchanged.
- G methods untouched.

## Exit criteria

- Analytical null implemented for S1, S2, L1, C2ST
- `make validate-null` passes on real corpus
- Tests pass; PR merged
